# cppcheck suppressions for the multi-asset pricing engine.
#
# passedByValue on the AD scalar types (Dual, Dual2) and the scalar-generic
# Black-Scholes is a deliberate, correct design choice, NOT a defect:
#
#   * Dual (16B) and Dual2 (24B) are tiny arithmetic value types. Passing them
#     by value lets the compiler keep them in registers and inline the chain-
#     rule arithmetic; const-reference would add indirection and pessimize the
#     hot automatic-differentiation loop. This mirrors how std::complex and
#     other small numeric value types are passed.
#   * bs_price_generic is templated on the scalar type T; for T = double the
#     "pass by value" is obviously right, and for the Dual/Dual2/CtDouble
#     instantiations the same register-passing argument applies.
#
# cppcheck's heuristic only flags types above ~16 bytes, which is why Dual
# itself isn't reported but Dual2 is — the inconsistency confirms it's a size
# heuristic, not a real performance problem.
passedByValue:core/include/mape/autodiff.hpp
passedByValue:core/include/mape/models/black_scholes_ad.hpp
